'''Cycles per byte''' (sometimes abbreviated '''cpb''') is a [[unit of measurement]] which indicates the number of [[clock cycles]] a [[microprocessor]] will perform per [[byte]] (usually of [[Octet (computing)|octet]] size) of data processed in an [[algorithm]].<ref name=ibm>{{cite web|url=http://publib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/systems/scope/hw/index.jsp?topic=/iphb1/iphb1_vios_planning_sea_procs.htm|title=Processor allocation}}</ref> It is commonly used as a partial indicator of real-world [[Algorithmic efficiency|performance]] in [[cryptographic]] [[Function (computer science)|functions]].<ref name=skein>{{cite web|url=http://skein-hash.info/sha3-engineering|title=Engineering comparison of SHA-3 candidates}}</ref>

