{{Infobox scientist |name = Hilary Ann Priestley |image = |image_size = |alma_mater = [[University of Oxford]] |alt = Hilary Priestley |birth_date = |doctoral_advisor = David Edwards<ref name="mgp">{{MathGenealogy|35776}}.</ref> |thesis_title = Topics in Ordered Topological Spaces, Including a Representation Theory for Distributive Lattices<ref name="mgp" /> |thesis_year = 1970 |workplaces = [[University of Oxford]] |nationality = British |fields = [[Lattice theory]], [[universal algebra]], [[mathematical logic]] }}
'''Hilary Ann Priestley''' is a British [[mathematician]]. She is a professor at the [[University of Oxford]] and a Fellow of [[St Anne's College, Oxford]], where she has been Tutor in Mathematics since 1972.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gardam|first=Tim|title=Titles of Distinction awarded to eight Fellows|url=http://www.st-annes.ox.ac.uk/about/news/item/article/titles-of-distinction-awarded-to-ei|date=11 July 2006|accessdate=2014-06-11}}</ref>
Hilary Priestley introduced ordered separable topological spaces that are important in the study of distributive lattices; such topological spaces are now usually called [[Priestley space]]s in her honour.<ref>{{cite journal| journal=[[Semigroup Forum]] | date=December 1980 | volume=20 | number=1 | pages=293–297 | title=A partially ordered space which is not a priestley space | first=Albert | last=Stralka | publisher=[[Springer (publisher)|Springer]] | doi=10.1007/BF02572690 }}</ref> The term "[[Priestley duality]]" is also used.<ref>{{cite journal| journal=[[Order (journal)|Order]] | date=September 1991 | volume=8 | number=3 | pages=299–315 | title=Remarks on Priestley duality for distributive lattices | first1=R. | last1=Cignoli | first2=S. | last2=Lafalce | first3=A. | last3=Petrovich | publisher=[[Springer (publisher)|Springer]] | doi=10.1007/BF00383451 }}</ref> In addition, Priestly has contributed to the [[Distributive lattice#representation theory|representation theory of distributive lattices]].{{fact|date=February 2018}}
Following Priestley's academic advisors back by 15 generations on the [[Mathematics Genealogy Project]] database, one arrives at [[Isaac Newton]].<ref name="mgp" />
